WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.030
[Music]

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:12.510
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today we're&nbsp;
going to talk about factoring polynomials and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.510 --> 00:00:20.220
poly numbers. First, I'll review some basic facts&nbsp;
about factoring with ordinary natural numbers.

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:30.000
So, a few definitions just to remind you: if 2&nbsp;
times 3 equals 6, we say that 6 is a multiple&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:41.340
of 2 or a multiple of 3, and we say that 2 and&nbsp;
3 are divisors or factors of 6. If we take a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.340 --> 00:00:48.330
bigger number like, say, 1001, then it could&nbsp;
be factored in a number of different ways to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.330 --> 00:00:56.370
be written as 77 times 13, or 7 times 143, or&nbsp;
as 1 times 1001—that's also a factorization.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.370 --> 00:01:01.830
So although it may appear that there are lots of&nbsp;
different ways of factoring a number, there's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.830 --> 00:01:07.680
very important and fundamental theorem called, in&nbsp;
fact, the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:14.610
says that every natural number can, in fact, be&nbsp;
factored uniquely—in other words, in only one way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.610 --> 00:01:22.740
up to order—into prime factors. A prime number, I&nbsp;
remind you, is a number that only has two factors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:35.370
namely 1 and itself, for example, 3, 5, 7, 11,&nbsp;
13, 17, 19, and so on. So the Fundamental Theorem&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.370 --> 00:01:41.580
of Arithmetic means that we can express every&nbsp;
natural number as a product of prime numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.580 --> 00:01:48.780
and there's only one way of doing that up to&nbsp;
the order in which we present those primes.

00:01:48.780 --> 00:02:04.260
So, for example, 1001 is 7 times 11 times 13.&nbsp;
1002 is 2 times 3 times 167. 267 is prime. 1003&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:12.270
is 17 times 59. 1004 is 2 squared times 251.&nbsp;
There's no reason why a prime factor can't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.270 --> 00:02:20.220
appear more than once in the factorization of a&nbsp;
number. There's 1005 and 1006, and this already&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.220 --> 00:02:29.130
indicates a major interesting aspect of this: that&nbsp;
factoring large numbers is highly unpredictable.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:36.630
It's not at all obvious how to extend this&nbsp;
table to the next twenty or thirty. There are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.630 --> 00:02:40.620
a few patterns that are kind of obvious—I mean,&nbsp;
obviously, every even number is divisible by 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:45.540
and if this number is divisible by 3, then the&nbsp;
one after it is also going to be divisible by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:53.100
3—but aside from those relatively trivial remarks,&nbsp;
it's very hard to predict how a random big number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.100 --> 00:03:02.010
factors into primes. And that's a major important&nbsp;
fact when it comes to encoding or encrypting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:07.440
information, say, on the internet. This unique&nbsp;
factorization theorem plays a very important role.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:14.130
Alright, so we're not going to prove these facts.&nbsp;
These are kind of standard facts—there's nothing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.130 --> 00:03:19.050
problematic about them, I think, once you've&nbsp;
set up arithmetic as we have done. But we are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:25.620
going to be interested in extending this kind&nbsp;
of thinking to poly numbers and polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:29.760
which are, as we've seen last time,&nbsp;
just certain types of poly numbers.

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:37.410
The poly number (1, 2) times the poly number (3,&nbsp;
5) is the poly number (3, 11, 10). So we say that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.410 --> 00:03:44.490
(3, 11, 10) is a multiple of (1, 2) or a multiple&nbsp;
of (3, 5). Now, we say that (1, 2) and (3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:53.520
5) are factors or divisors of (3, 11, 10). And a&nbsp;
natural question is, suppose we were given (3, 11,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:53.520 --> 00:04:01.650
10)—how could we find its factors? Well, for that,&nbsp;
it helps to look at the general formula. If we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.650 --> 00:04:13.470
multiply the binomial (a, b) with the binomial (c,&nbsp;
d), we get (ac, ad + bc, bd). That's a trinomial.

00:04:13.470 --> 00:04:21.690
So if we stare at this, it helps us solve this&nbsp;
problem. For example, suppose you're given the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:29.460
trinomial (7, 45, 18), and you want to write it as&nbsp;
(a, b) times (c, d) for some (a, b) and some (c,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:39.090
d). Well, then ac has got to be 7, and these are&nbsp;
natural numbers. a and c are either (1, 7) or (7,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:48.630
1). In other words, the set {a, c} has got to be&nbsp;
equal to the set {1, 7}. Similarly, bd has got&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:48.630 --> 00:04:54.960
to equal 18. So now there are more possibilities&nbsp;
because 18 is not prime; they could be (1, 18),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.470 --> 00:05:04.110
(2, 9), or (3, 6) in either order. And there's&nbsp;
one more piece of information: the middle term,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.110 --> 00:05:13.980
ad + bc—this times this plus this times this—has&nbsp;
got to equal 45. And now it's a standard kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:20.040
little game at one place, looking at all the&nbsp;
possibilities. How could we choose these two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:27.300
numbers? Now, how do we choose a pair here so&nbsp;
that the a times the d plus the b times the c&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.300 --> 00:05:34.770
should equal 45? Well, there's only going to be&nbsp;
one way, and that turns out to be the solution. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.770 --> 00:05:41.550
we tried 1 times 9 plus 7 times 2—well, that&nbsp;
wouldn't work. We've got 1 times 3 plus 6 times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:50.520
7—1 times 3 plus 6 times 7—that would work, giving&nbsp;
us 45. And so that's how we get the factorization,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:55.140
by essentially looking through all the&nbsp;
possibilities encoded by these 3 equations.

00:05:55.140 --> 00:06:01.980
In more familiar high school terms, what&nbsp;
we've done is we've taken the trinomial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:08.190
(7 + 45x + 18x²) and we've factored&nbsp;
it into two binomial expressions:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.190 --> 00:06:16.290
(1 + 6x) and (7 + 3x). We rather think&nbsp;
of this expression as representing this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.290 --> 00:06:22.050
equality between this polynomial and these&nbsp;
two polynomials—that's really the same thing.

00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:30.540
So at this point, it's probably a good exercise&nbsp;
for you to take a few binomial poly numbers and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:36.150
multiply them to get a trinomial, and then put&nbsp;
it aside for a day or two and then come back and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:45.450
see if you can factor those trinomials—go reverse&nbsp;
the process to find the factors. Some trinomials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:50.430
cannot be factored. If you just write down a&nbsp;
random one, then it's very likely that it cannot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:58.110
be factored. For example, it's not hard to see&nbsp;
that the poly number (1, 5, 1) cannot be factored&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.110 --> 00:07:05.850
into two binomials. So the question is, should we&nbsp;
call that kind of poly number a prime polynomial?

00:07:05.850 --> 00:07:17.730
However, an interesting complication arises&nbsp;
when we move from binomials and trinomials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:25.020
to slightly larger poly numbers, and here's a&nbsp;
very interesting example: the poly number (1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:36.960
-1, 1), which is itself a trinomial, times (1,&nbsp;
1, 1) is (1, 0, 1, 0, 1). So this poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:45.780
which is a positive poly number, factors, but&nbsp;
one of its factors—this one here—is a poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:52.200
number with a negative coefficient. Up to now,&nbsp;
we have not been including this possibility;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:58.410
we've only restricted ourselves to positive&nbsp;
coefficients. But it turns out that if we do that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:05.430
we miss out on this phenomenon here. And this&nbsp;
is something that's quite different between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.430 --> 00:08:12.780
polynomials or poly numbers and ordinary natural&nbsp;
numbers. For ordinary natural number division&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:19.320
or factorization, negative numbers play no&nbsp;
essential role. However, for poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:26.160
they play a very important role. Certain&nbsp;
factorizations are possible with negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:31.020
coefficients that are simply not possible&nbsp;
if you restrict to positive coefficients.

00:08:31.020 --> 00:08:37.470
So the mathematics is forcing us to&nbsp;
enlarge our view. We're going to have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.470 --> 00:08:42.570
to move from positive poly numbers to&nbsp;
talking about integral poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:48.090
And what is an integral poly number? It's an&nbsp;
expression just like a positive poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:52.350
except that the entries&nbsp;
are allowed to be integers.

00:08:55.190 --> 00:09:02.210
This defines a new mathematical object called&nbsp;
an integral poly number, and we'll give it this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.210 --> 00:09:12.680
title: poly-int, for integral poly number. This&nbsp;
is a very nice realm for doing arithmetic with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.680 --> 00:09:19.310
poly numbers. It's, in fact, better in many ways&nbsp;
than sticking to positive poly numbers. So we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.310 --> 00:09:24.740
going to have to do that now. We're going to have&nbsp;
to rethink what we've done, move to integral poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.740 --> 00:09:29.630
numbers, and investigate the arithmetic of&nbsp;
these. When we do that, we will see that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:35.630
primes and fundamental theorems come into focus&nbsp;
for us, and it becomes very rich and beautiful.

00:09:35.630 --> 00:09:41.090
So next time, it's arithmetic&nbsp;
with integral poly numbers. I hope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.090 --> 00:09:45.170
you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:45.170 --> 00:09:45.200
[Music]

